-- South African Stocks Extends Gains, Led Higher by African Eagle, AngloGold
-- Janice Kew
-- 2010-06-15T12:24:46Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-15/south-african-stocks-extends-gains-led-higher-by-african-eagle-anglogold.html

          
          
             South Africa’s  FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index  rose 175.76, or 0.6 percent, to 27,621.85 by 2:15
p.m. in Johannesburg, extending yesterday’s 2.2 percent gain.  
 The following are among the most active stocks in the South
African market today.  
 African Eagle Resources Plc  (AEA SJ) rose for the first
time in more than a month, climbing 2 cents, or 4.4 percent, to
47 cents. The metals explorer said it found more nickel than
expected at its Dutwa project in Tanzania.  
 AngloGold Ashanti Ltd.  (ANG SJ), Africa’s largest gold
producer, climbed 4.02 rand, or 1.2 percent, to 330.97 rand,
heading for its highest close in a week. Gold gained in London
as demand for the precious metal rose after Greece’s credit
rating was cut to junk, increasing concern that Europe’s debt
crisis may worsen.  
 Blue Financial Services Ltd.  (BFS SJ) dropped 6 cents, or
29 percent, to 15 cents, heading for its biggest drop since
March 2009. The provider of unsecured loans said it will post a
fiscal full-year loss of between 1 billion rand ($130 million)
and 1.05 billion rand, while Chief Executive Officer  Dave van Niekerk  said he plans to quit as the company faces losses 10
times bigger than Blue’s market value.  
 Cie Financiere Richemont SA  (CFR SJ), the world’s second-
largest luxury-goods maker, dropped 43 cents, or 1.5 percent, to
27.85 rand. German investor confidence plunged in June on
concern that the sovereign debt crisis will undermine export
prospects and crimp growth in Europe’s largest economy.  
 Coal of Africa Ltd.  (CZA SJ) gained for a third day,
climbing 20 cents, or 1.6 percent, to 12.70 rand. The coal
producer said it received government approval to mine coking
coal at its Vele project.  
 Naspers Ltd.  (NPN SJ), which has a 35 percent stake in
Tencent Holdings Ltd., dropped 3 rand, or 1.1 percent, to 270
rand. Tencent (700 HK), China’s biggest Internet company by
market value, lost 3.1 percent to HK$127.40 after the company
said Chairman  Ma Huateng  sold 5 million shares for an average
price of HK$102.70 apiece.  
